{
  "The shaft of a long bone is called the:": "",
  "Diaphysis": "",
  "Periosteum": "",
  "Epiphysis": "",
  "Endosteum": "",
  "The diaphysis is the long, cylindrical shaft of a long bone and is composed primarily of compact bone surrounding the medullary cavity.": "",
  "Red bone marrow is the primary site of:": "",
  "Nerve transmission": "",
  "Hematopoiesis (blood cell formation)": "",
  "Mineral storage": "",
  "Fat storage": "",
  "Red bone marrow is responsible for hematopoiesis, which is the production of red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets.": "",
  "The periosteum covers which part of the bone?": "",
  "The outer bone surface except at joint surfaces": "",
  "Only the epiphysis": "",
  "The inner marrow cavity": "",
  "Joint surfaces": "",
  "The periosteum is a tough, fibrous membrane that covers the outer surface of bone everywhere except where articular cartilage is present at joint surfaces.": "",
  "Compact bone is found primarily in the:": "",
  "Marrow cavity": "",
  "Growth plate": "",
  "Epiphysis interior": "",
  "Diaphysis (shaft)": "",
  "The diaphysis is composed primarily of dense compact bone, which provides the strength and rigidity needed to support body weight and resist bending.": "",
  "Spongy (cancellous) bone is found in the:": "",
  "Interior of the epiphysis": "",
  "Articular cartilage": "",
  "Shaft of the bone": "",
  "Spongy bone fills the interior of the epiphyses and consists of a network of trabeculae that provide strength while reducing overall bone weight.": "",
  "Bones store which important minerals?": "",
  "Calcium and phosphorus": "",
  "Magnesium only": "",
  "Sodium and potassium": "",
  "Iron and zinc only": "",
  "Bones serve as the body's primary reservoir for calcium and phosphorus, which can be released into the bloodstream as needed to maintain mineral homeostasis.": "",
  "How many bones does the adult human skeleton contain?": "",
  "100": "",
  "150": "",
  "206": "",
  "300": "",
  "The adult human skeleton typically contains 206 bones, which is fewer than the approximately 270 bones present at birth due to fusion during development.": "",
  "The Haversian (osteon) system is a structural unit of:": "",
  "Spongy bone": "",
  "Cartilage": "",
  "Bone marrow": "",
  "Compact bone": "",
  "The osteon (Haversian system) is the fundamental structural unit of compact bone, consisting of concentric lamellae surrounding a central canal containing blood vessels and nerves.": "",
  "Yellow bone marrow stores:": "",
  "Minerals": "",
  "Blood cells": "",
  "Fat (energy reserve)": "",
  "Water": "",
  "Yellow bone marrow consists primarily of adipose (fat) tissue that fills the medullary cavity of long bones in adults and serves as an energy reserve.": "",
  "The epiphyseal plate is important for:": "",
  "Blood cell production": "",
  "Muscle attachment": "",
  "Longitudinal bone growth": "",
  "The epiphyseal plate (growth plate) is a region of hyaline cartilage between the epiphysis and diaphysis where new cartilage is produced and then ossified, allowing bones to grow in length.": "",
  "What is the diaphysis?": "",
  "The rounded end of a long bone": "",
  "The growth plate between bone regions": "",
  "The elongated shaft of a long bone": "",
  "The membrane covering the bone surface": "",
  "The diaphysis is the elongated, cylindrical shaft that forms the main body of a long bone and is composed of a thick collar of compact bone surrounding the medullary cavity.": "",
  "What is the epiphysis?": "",
  "The shaft of a long bone": "",
  "The rounded end of a long bone that forms joints with adjacent bones": "",
  "The tough outer covering of a bone": "",
  "The inner lining of the marrow cavity": "",
  "The epiphysis is the expanded, rounded end of a long bone filled with spongy bone and covered with articular cartilage where it participates in joint formation.": "",
  "What is the endosteum?": "",
  "The growth plate of a developing bone": "",
  "The cartilage covering joint surfaces": "",
  "The thin membrane lining the medullary (marrow) cavity": "",
  "The outer fibrous membrane covering the bone": "",
  "The endosteum is a thin connective tissue membrane that lines the inner surface of the medullary cavity and contains osteoblasts and osteoclasts important for bone remodeling.": "",
  "What does hematopoiesis mean?": "",
  "The hardening of soft tissue": "",
  "The process of bone resorption": "",
  "The formation of cartilage tissue": "",
  "The production of blood cells": "",
  "Hematopoiesis literally means 'blood making' and refers to the production of all types of blood cells, which occurs primarily in red bone marrow.": "",
  "What is an osteocyte?": "",
  "A bone-forming cell that secretes new matrix": "",
  "A mature bone cell embedded in lacunae that maintains bone tissue": "",
  "A stem cell found in bone marrow": "",
  "A large cell that breaks down bone tissue": "",
  "An osteocyte is a mature bone cell trapped within a lacuna in the bone matrix, responsible for maintaining the bone tissue and communicating with other bone cells through canaliculi.": "",
  "What is an osteoblast?": "",
  "A mature bone cell residing in lacunae": "",
  "A cell that dissolves bone tissue": "",
  "A cartilage cell found in the growth plate": "",
  "A bone-forming cell that synthesizes and secretes new bone matrix": "",
  "An osteoblast is a bone-forming cell that synthesizes and secretes the organic components of bone matrix (osteoid) and helps regulate its mineralization.": "",
  "What is an osteoclast?": "",
  "A cell that builds new bone tissue": "",
  "A mature bone cell that senses mechanical stress": "",
  "A type of blood cell produced in the marrow": "",
  "A large multinucleated cell that breaks down and resorbs bone tissue": "",
  "An osteoclast is a large, multinucleated cell derived from monocyte precursors that secretes acids and enzymes to dissolve bone matrix in a process called bone resorption.": "",
  "What is Wolff's law?": "",
  "The principle that bone remodels and strengthens in response to mechanical stress": "",
  "The principle that bone cannot repair itself after fracture": "",
  "The principle that bone grows only during childhood": "",
  "The principle that bone weakens with repeated use": "",
  "Wolff's law states that bone adapts to the loads placed upon it, becoming stronger and thicker in areas of increased mechanical stress and weaker in areas of reduced stress.": "",
  "What is the medullary cavity?": "",
  "The area where the growth plate is located": "",
  "A hollow space inside the diaphysis that contains marrow": "",
  "The space between two vertebrae": "",
  "The joint space filled with synovial fluid": "",
  "The medullary cavity is the central hollow space within the diaphysis of a long bone that is lined by the endosteum and filled with yellow bone marrow in adults.": "",
  "What does articular cartilage mean?": "",
  "A thin layer of hyaline cartilage covering the bone surface at a joint": "",
  "Cartilage that forms the growth plate": "",
  "Cartilage found in the ear and nose only": "",
  "Cartilage that produces blood cells": "",
  "Articular cartilage is a smooth layer of hyaline cartilage that covers the epiphysis at joint surfaces, reducing friction and absorbing shock during movement.": "",
  "A 14-year-old athlete is told by her doctor that she should not take certain supplements that could prematurely close her growth plates. Which bone structure is the doctor concerned about?": "",
  "The medullary cavity": "",
  "The endosteum": "",
  "The periosteum": "",
  "The epiphyseal plate": "",
  "The epiphyseal plate is the cartilaginous growth plate responsible for longitudinal bone growth. Premature closure would permanently stop the bone from growing in length, potentially stunting the athlete's height.": "",
  "A patient with severe anemia is found to have a disease affecting the interior of her flat bones and the ends of her long bones. Which tissue is most likely affected?": "",
  "Yellow bone marrow": "",
  "Red bone marrow": "",
  "Red bone marrow is found in the spongy bone of flat bones and epiphyses of long bones and is responsible for hematopoiesis. Disease affecting this tissue would impair blood cell production, leading to anemia.": "",
  "An astronaut returns from six months on the International Space Station and a bone density scan reveals significant bone loss. Which principle of bone biology best explains this finding?": "",
  "Bones only grow during adolescence": "",
  "Space radiation destroys osteoblasts": "",
  "The periosteum degrades in low oxygen environments": "",
  "Wolff's law: without mechanical stress, bone is resorbed": "",
  "According to Wolff's law, bone remodels in response to the mechanical stresses placed on it. In microgravity, the absence of weight-bearing stress causes osteoclast activity to exceed osteoblast activity, resulting in bone loss.": "",
  "A child sustains a fracture that damages the region between the diaphysis and the epiphysis of the femur. The orthopedic surgeon is concerned about future growth. Which structure was likely damaged?": "",
  "The periosteum of the shaft": "",
  "The epiphyseal plate (growth plate)": "",
  "The articular cartilage at the knee": "",
  "The endosteum lining the medullary cavity": "",
  "The epiphyseal plate sits between the diaphysis and the epiphysis and is responsible for longitudinal bone growth. Damage to this cartilaginous structure in a growing child can impair or halt future bone lengthening.": "",
  "A medical student is examining a cross-section of a long bone under a microscope and observes concentric rings of bone matrix surrounding a central canal. What structure is the student viewing?": "",
  "An epiphyseal plate": "",
  "Spongy bone trabeculae": "",
  "An osteon (Haversian system)": "",
  "The osteon (Haversian system) is the structural unit of compact bone, featuring concentric lamellae arranged around a central Haversian canal that carries blood vessels and nerves.": "",
  "A 70-year-old patient needs a bone marrow biopsy. The physician chooses to sample from the sternum rather than the femoral shaft. Why is this location preferred?": "",
  "The femur is too deep to access safely": "",
  "The sternum contains more compact bone": "",
  "The sternum is easier to sterilize before the procedure": "",
  "The sternum retains active red bone marrow throughout life, whereas the femoral shaft contains mostly yellow marrow in adults": "",
  "In adults, red bone marrow (which produces blood cells) is concentrated in flat bones like the sternum and hip, while the medullary cavity of the femoral shaft is predominantly filled with yellow (fatty) marrow.": "",
  "A surgeon performing a bone graft carefully preserves the periosteum on the donor bone. Why is this membrane so important for successful healing?": "",
  "It stores calcium that will be used during the healing process": "",
  "It produces synovial fluid to lubricate the graft site": "",
  "It contains osteogenic cells and blood vessels essential for bone repair and nutrition": "",
  "It prevents the graft from being rejected by the immune system": "",
  "The periosteum contains osteogenic (bone-forming) cells in its inner layer and a rich blood supply that are critical for bone nutrition, growth, and repair following surgical procedures.": "",
  "A lab technician is studying bone tissue and notices small channels connecting lacunae to one another and to the central canal. A colleague asks what function these channels serve. What is the best answer?": "",
  "They allow blood cells to exit the bone": "",
  "They store excess calcium during periods of low demand": "",
  "They are empty spaces left behind by osteoclast activity": "",
  "They are canaliculi that allow osteocytes to communicate and exchange nutrients and waste": "",
  "Canaliculi are tiny channels in bone matrix that connect the lacunae of neighboring osteocytes to each other and to the central Haversian canal, allowing nutrient and waste exchange that keeps osteocytes alive.": "",
  "A physical therapist recommends weight-bearing exercises for a patient recovering from a leg fracture. The patient asks how exercise helps bones heal. Which response is most accurate?": "",
  "Weight-bearing compresses yellow marrow into red marrow, increasing healing speed": "",
  "Mechanical stress stimulates osteoblasts to deposit new bone, strengthening the healing site": "",
  "Exercise stretches the periosteum, which triggers pain signals that accelerate repair": "",
  "Exercise increases blood calcium levels, which directly deposits onto the fracture": "",
  "According to Wolff's law, mechanical stress from weight-bearing exercise stimulates osteoblast activity and new bone deposition at the site of stress, helping the fracture site remodel into stronger bone.": "",
  "During a forensic investigation, a bone fragment is found. The analyst determines it has a thick wall of compact bone, a hollow medullary cavity, and expanded ends with spongy bone. What type of bone is this fragment most likely from?": "",
  "A flat bone such as the scapula": "",
  "An irregular bone such as a vertebra": "",
  "A long bone such as the femur or humerus": "",
  "A short bone such as a carpal": "",
  "The described features, including a thick compact bone shaft with a medullary cavity and expanded spongy bone ends, are characteristic of a long bone like the femur, humerus, or tibia.": ""
